==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fr|capitalisme|t=the condition of one who is rich}}; equivalent to {{af|en|capital|-ism}}. First used in English by novelist [[w:William Thackeray|William Thackeray]] in 1854.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈkæpɪt(ə)lɪz(ə)m/|lang=en}}
* {{a|GA}} {{enPR|kăpʹĭ-tl-ĭz'm}}, {{IPA|/ˈkæpɪ̈tl̩ˌɪzm̩/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|politics|uncountable}} a socio-economic system based on [[private]] ownership of resources or [[capital]].
# {{lb|en|economics|uncountable}} an economic system based on [[private]] ownership of the means of [[production]] and their operation for [[profit]].
# {{lb|en|politics|economic liberalism|uncountable}} a socio-economic system based on [[private]] property rights, including the [[private]] ownership of resources or [[capital]], with economic decisions made largely through the operation of a market [[unregulated]] by the [[state]].
# {{lb|en|economics|economic liberalism|uncountable}} an economic system based on the abstraction of resources into the form of privately owned [[capital]], with economic decisions made largely through the operation of a market [[unregulated]] by the [[state]].
# {{lb|en|countable}} a specific variation or implementation of such a socio-economic system.

